   "source": [
    "## **3. Methodology**"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "6bdd6e67-bf05-48d7-ac92-e3015929ece1",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### **3.1 Clustering algorithms**"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "daefe55a-d554-4e80-9bb2-421f300a6f28",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### 3.1.1 KMeans"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "c97759c1-e430-4276-911c-dd4fc0f27fbd",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "KMeans is a partitional clustering algorithm that seeks to partition n observations into k clusters in which each observation belongs to the cluster with the nearest mean (centroid). The algorithm iteratively updates centroids and reassigns data points until convergence.\n",
    "\n",
    "Mathematically, KMeans aims to minimize the within-cluster sum of squares (WCSS):"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "15ce2368-b9d6-4741-a1cd-dffdaff58718",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "![Công thức toán học](images/311kmeans.png)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "3bfb1829-7239-4f53-a52c-9a96e42868c9",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "where μi is the centroid of cluster 𝐶𝑖"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "c0510ccb-ea4c-4ad5-9be0-ec46fbabcaa5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "***Strengths:***\n",
    "\n",
    "+ Computationally efficient (time complexity approximately O(n⋅k⋅d⋅t), with d dimensions and t iterations).\n",
    "\n",
    "+ Simple and widely used in practice.\n",
    "\n",
    "***Limitations:***\n",
    "\n",
    "+ Requires the number of clusters (k) to be specified a priori.\n",
    "\n",
    "+ Assumes spherical clusters of similar size.\n",
    "\n",
    "+ Sensitive to initialization."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "fb92f5e0-485f-495d-a352-2c5be61c65e7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### 3.1.2 Gaussian Mixture Model (GMM)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "88d0405f-e6c4-43ff-8f7f-eb66cf245c0e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The Gaussian Mixture Model is a probabilistic model that represents the data as a mixture of several Gaussian distributions, each corresponding to a cluster. Instead of assigning each point to a single cluster, GMM computes membership probabilities.\n",
    "\n",
    "The model estimates parameters using the Expectation-Maximization (EM) algorithm, which iteratively maximizes the likelihood function."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "9e5f956b-0d54-441b-8b3f-013b7c465d76",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "![Công thức toán học](images/312gmm.png)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0525dfbe-c2e5-4930-af4a-d541c5669bbf",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "where 𝜋𝑖 are the mixture weights, 𝜇𝑖 the means, and Σ𝑖 the covariance matrices."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "1b054cb2-c473-4c3c-b4df-98a8766e146b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "***Strengths:***\n",
    "\n",
    "+ Can model elliptical clusters with varying sizes and orientations.\n",
    "\n",
    "+ Provides probabilistic cluster memberships, useful for soft clustering.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Limitations:**\n",
    "\n",
    "+ Requires the number of components (k) to be specified.\n",
    "\n",
    "+ Sensitive to initialization and can converge to local optima."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ca0af49c-d67f-4221-a19b-44a48f9cf29c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### **3.2 Model selection and parameter tuning**"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "5b3f0728-7880-4e1d-a84b-010ce30cb8d0",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Selecting appropriate models and tuning their hyperparameters are critical steps in unsupervised learning, as these decisions directly impact the interpretability and validity of clustering results. To ensure methodological rigor, this study adopted well-established techniques for determining the optimal number of clusters and model parameters. The following sections describe each method, its theoretical foundation, and practical application."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f536f832-ea97-4880-a94e-7a85ccce023f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### 3.2.1 Elbow method and Silhouette Score for KMeans"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f1e3f878-5102-4a59-8da3-d4fba69e1bb9",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "* Elbow Method\n",
    "\n",
    "The Elbow Method is one of the most common approaches to estimate the optimal number of clusters (k) in partitional clustering algorithms such as KMeans and Gaussian Mixture Models (GMM). The method involves calculating the Within-Cluster Sum of Squares (WCSS) for different values of k. The WCSS typically decreases as k increases because clusters are smaller and better fitted to the data. However, after a certain point, adding more clusters results in only marginal gains. The “elbow” point on the plot of WCSS versus k indicates the value of k beyond which the marginal gain drops sharply.\n",
    "\n",
    "This approach is grounded in the principle of balancing model complexity and goodness-of-fit (James et al., 2013). By selecting k at the elbow, we mitigate the risk of overfitting while capturing sufficient structure in the data.\n",
    "\n",
    "* Silhouette Score\n",
    "\n",
    "To complement the Elbow Method, the Silhouette Score provides a quantitative validation of clustering consistency. For each observation, the Silhouette Coefficient compares the mean intra-cluster distance (cohesion) with the mean nearest-cluster distance (separation). The score ranges from -1 to 1, where higher values indicate that samples are well matched to their own cluster and poorly matched to neighboring clusters.\n",
    "\n",
    "A high average Silhouette Score suggests that the clusters are dense and well separated, thus supporting the selection of k. This metric is especially valuable because it is independent of the method used to generate clusters."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "id": "3f4f3148-fe68-44d9-81ab-dc373b0965cf",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from sklearn.cluster import KMeans\n",
    "from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "\n",
    "inertia = []\n",
    "silhouette_scores = []\n",
    "K_range = range(2, 10)  # Try K=2 to 9\n",
    "\n",
    "for k in K_range:\n",
    "    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42, n_init=10)\n",
    "    labels = kmeans.fit_predict(pca_df)\n",
    "    inertia.append(kmeans.inertia_)\n",
    "    silhouette_scores.append(silhouette_score(pca_df, labels))"
   ]
  },
